---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import TerminalBlock from "../components/TerminalBlock.astro";
import ChapterHeading from "../components/ChapterHeading.astro";
import ModesTable from "../components/ModesTable.astro";
import VaultCompare from "../components/VaultCompare.astro";

const installCmd =
  "curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/patrickmvla/bocek/main/install.sh | bash";
---

<Base title="bocek — Claude Code modes with a vault">
  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="relative overflow-hidden">
    <div class="hero-wash pointer-events-none absolute inset-0"></div>
    <div class="relative mx-auto max-w-5xl px-6 pt-20 pb-28 sm:pt-28 sm:pb-36">
      <div class="mb-8 flex items-center gap-3">
        <span
          class="font-heading text-[10px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.3em] text-[color:var(--accent-amber)]"
          >bocek · v0</span
        >
        <span class="h-px w-12 bg-border"></span>
        <span
          class="font-heading text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.25em] text-muted-foreground"
          >for claude code</span
        >
      </div>

      <h1
        class="font-heading text-4xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-foreground sm:text-6xl sm:leading-[1.05]"
      >
        Claude Code with modes,
        <br />
        <span class="text-muted-foreground"
          >and a vault that remembers why.</span
        >
      </h1>

      <p
        class="mt-8 max-w-2xl font-sans text-lg leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground"
      >
        Six slash commands flip Claude between reasoning and coding. A hook
        blocks source-file writes while you're still deciding. Every resolved
        decision — with its evidence and its rejected alternatives — lands in
        <code
          class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.9em] text-foreground"
          >.bocek/vault/</code
        > and ships with your repo.
      </p>

      <div class="mt-10">
        <TerminalBlock command={installCmd} title="~ — install bocek" />
      </div>

      <p
        class="mt-4 font-mono text-[11px] tracking-tight text-muted-foreground"
      >
        then <code
          class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[11px] text-foreground"
          >bocek on</code
        > in your project — adds <code
          class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[11px] text-foreground"
          >/design</code
        >, <code
          class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[11px] text-foreground"
          >/research</code
        >, <code
          class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[11px] text-foreground"
          >/implementation</code
        >, <code
          class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[11px] text-foreground"
          >/debugging</code
        >, <code
          class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[11px] text-foreground"
          >/refactoring</code
        >, <code
          class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[11px] text-foreground"
          >/review</code
        >
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 01 — the problem -->
  <ChapterHeading
    id="problem"
    number="01"
    title="How mediocre software gets written with an AI assistant."
    kicker="the problem"
  >
    <div class="space-y-6 text-base leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
      <p>
        Day one. You type
        <span class="text-foreground">"build me a checkout API."</span> The model
        generates route handlers from its training-data defaults. Nobody asked
        which inventory locking strategy applied under your write volume.
        Nobody checked how Stripe actually handles idempotency. Nobody wrote
        down why REST instead of GraphQL. It compiled, the happy path works,
        you move on.
      </p>
      <p>
        Month three. You ask the model to add a feature. It doesn't know auth
        was supposed to be JWT with a 15-minute expiry — that decision was
        never made, only assumed. It generates session-based auth. The project
        now has two auth systems. Nobody can tell you why.
      </p>
      <p>
        Month six. Inventory deadlocks under load. You ask the model to fix
        it. It doesn't know the locking strategy was supposed to be deliberate
        — because it wasn't. It "fixes" the deadlock by removing the lock.
        Inventory goes negative in production.
      </p>

      <p class="text-foreground">
        This is compounding. Every ungrounded decision makes the next decision
        worse, because the model has less ground truth to reason from. By
        decision twenty, the model can't help — it doesn't know which
        behaviors are intentional and which are accidents. Neither do you.
      </p>
    </div>
  </ChapterHeading>

  <!-- 02 — the shift -->
  <ChapterHeading
    id="shift"
    number="02"
    title="The model knows more than it gives you."
    kicker="the shift"
    variant="alt"
  >
    <div class="space-y-6 text-base leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
      <p>
        An LLM is a prediction engine. It produces the most statistically
        likely output given its training data, which is mostly average code —
        Stack Overflow, tutorials, boilerplate, unremarkable production repos.
        Ask for output and you get the median of all that.
      </p>
      <p>
        But the same model has read every architectural post-mortem, every
        scaling failure, every production incident write-up that was
        published. It knows how Stripe handles idempotency. It knows why
        optimistic locking fails under flash sales. That knowledge sits below
        the surface — a strong default pulls it toward the average.
      </p>

      <div
        class="my-4 grid gap-px overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-border/60 sm:grid-cols-2"
      >
        <div class="bg-background p-6">
          <div class="mb-3 flex items-center gap-2">
            <span class="h-1.5 w-1.5 rounded-full bg-muted-foreground/60"
            ></span>
            <span
              class="font-heading text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-muted-foreground"
              >executor</span
            >
          </div>
          <p
            class="font-mono text-[13px] leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground"
          >
            "Build me a checkout API."
          </p>
          <p class="mt-3 text-xs leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
            → the median of every checkout API in the training data
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-background p-6">
          <div class="mb-3 flex items-center gap-2">
            <span
              class="h-1.5 w-1.5 rounded-full bg-[color:var(--accent-amber)]"
            ></span>
            <span
              class="font-heading text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-[color:var(--accent-amber)]"
              >evidence source + adversarial reviewer</span
            >
          </div>
          <p class="font-mono text-[13px] leading-relaxed text-foreground">
            "Show me how Stripe handles idempotency in their node SDK. Then
            attack my approach to inventory locking."
          </p>
          <p class="mt-3 text-xs leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
            → the knowledge below the surface, filtered through your judgment
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        Bocek's primitives encode this shift as an operational contract. In
        <code
          class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
          >design</code
        > mode the model doesn't accept your plan — it takes a position,
        attacks its own recommendation harder than yours, and calibrates
        pushback to the quality of your reasoning. Sound reasoning gets
        accepted. Confident-but-wrong gets torn apart. Honest uncertainty gets
        helped. Impatience gets met with more pushback, because skipping
        reasoning is the signal that reasoning is needed.
      </p>
      <p class="text-foreground">
        This is code review, not conversation. You provide taste, context, and
        the final call. The model provides evidence, challenges, and
        execution. When it pushes back, that's the system working.
      </p>
    </div>
  </ChapterHeading>

  <!-- 03 — the loop -->
  <ChapterHeading
    id="loop"
    number="03"
    title="A session, start to finish."
    kicker="the loop"
  >
    <div class="space-y-6 text-base leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
      <p>
        You open Claude Code in the project and type <code
          class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.9em] text-foreground"
          >/design</code
        >.
      </p>

      <pre
        class="overflow-x-auto rounded-lg border border-border/60 bg-card px-5 py-4 font-mono text-[13px] leading-relaxed text-foreground"><code>/design
Checkout flow. Start with the decisions I haven't made.</code></pre>

      <p>
        Design is a reasoning mode. The hook blocks source-file writes until
        you switch to a coding mode — Claude can only ask, argue, and write to
        the vault.
      </p>

      <div
        class="rounded-lg border border-border/60 bg-background-alt/40 px-5 py-4 text-[15px] leading-relaxed text-foreground"
      >
        <div
          class="mb-2 font-heading text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-muted-foreground"
        >
          claude, in design mode
        </div>
        <p class="mb-2">
          You didn't say when inventory gets reserved. Three options —
        </p>
        <ul class="mb-2 space-y-0.5 pl-4 text-[14px]">
          <li>(a) at add-to-cart, 15-min expiry — Shopify's pattern.</li>
          <li>(b) at payment-start, 2-min expiry — Amazon's.</li>
          <li>(c) no lock, reconcile on conflict — low volume only.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          I'd argue for (a) at under 50 writes/sec. Under flash sales it
          starves legitimate buyers. So: what's your peak write volume, and do
          you run flash sales?
        </p>
      </div>

      <p>
        You answer. The model either records the decision or escalates and
        demands more defense. When a question resolves, it writes the
        reasoning trail to the vault:
      </p>

      <pre
        class="overflow-x-auto rounded-lg border border-border/60 bg-card px-5 py-4 font-mono text-[12px] leading-relaxed text-foreground"><code>.bocek/vault/checkout/optimistic-locking.md

# Optimistic locking for inventory decrement

## Chosen
Optimistic locking with retry. Reservation: 15 min from add-to-cart.

## Rejected
- Pessimistic row-level lock — blocks during the Stripe call.
- No lock + reconcile — breaks above write throughput.

## Rationale
Steady-state writes under 50/sec. Flash sales not on roadmap.
Conflict rate projected &lt;2%, retry cost is cheap.

## Revisit when
- Flash-sale feature gets scoped.
- Sustained write volume exceeds 200/sec.</code></pre>

      <p>
        When the vault holds enough decisions to ship, you type <code
          class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.9em] text-foreground"
          >/implementation</code
        >. The hook unlocks source-file writes. Implementation mode requires
        every function to open with a quote from the vault contract it
        satisfies — if a decision is missing, Claude stops and flags the gap
        instead of guessing.
      </p>

      <p class="text-foreground">
        The vault commits with your code. The next session reads it before
        writing a line.
      </p>
    </div>
  </ChapterHeading>

  <!-- 04 — the modes -->
  <ChapterHeading
    id="modes"
    number="04"
    title="Six modes. Each demands something from you."
    kicker="the modes"
    variant="alt"
  >
    <p
      class="mb-10 max-w-2xl text-base leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground"
    >
      Modes aren't features. They're contracts. The model doesn't accommodate
      weak reasoning — it escalates. You switch with a slash command; the
      contract for that mode loads, and the hook enforces what that mode can
      touch.
    </p>
    <ModesTable />
    <p
      class="mt-8 max-w-2xl text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground"
    >
      Modes are independent, not a pipeline. You switch whenever you need to
      — <code
        class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
        >/research</code
      > mid-design, <code
        class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
        >/debugging</code
      > mid-implementation, back to <code
        class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
        >/design</code
      > when a gap surfaces. The vault is how you carry work across the
      switches.
    </p>
  </ChapterHeading>

  <!-- 05 — enforcement -->
  <ChapterHeading
    id="enforcement"
    number="05"
    title="Context rot is structural. Three layers of defense cover the gap."
    kicker="enforcement"
  >
    <p class="mb-10 max-w-2xl text-base leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
      Every model degrades as context grows — 95% accuracy nosediving to 60%
      past a threshold (Chroma, 18 frontier models). Position bias is baked
      into the architecture — information in the middle of context loses
      roughly 30% attention. An instruction that says "don't write code in
      design mode" does not survive a long session. So Bocek doesn't rely on
      the model remembering its own contract.
    </p>

    <div class="divide-y divide-border/60 border-y border-border/60">
      <div class="grid gap-4 py-7 sm:grid-cols-[9rem_1fr] sm:gap-10">
        <div>
          <div
            class="font-heading text-[10px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-[color:var(--accent-amber)]"
          >
            layer 01
          </div>
          <div
            class="mt-1 font-heading text-base font-semibold text-foreground"
          >
            the hook
          </div>
        </div>
        <div
          class="space-y-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground"
        >
          <p>
            A bash script registered as a <code
              class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
              >PreToolUse</code
            > hook. It runs outside the context window, reads <code
              class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
              >.bocek/mode</code
            >, and either allows or denies the tool call before it reaches
            Claude. In reasoning modes it blocks <code
              class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
              >Edit</code
            >, <code
              class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
              >Write</code
            >, and the Bash workarounds the model actually reaches for —
            <code
              class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
              >sed&nbsp;-i</code
            >, <code
              class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
              >python&nbsp;-c</code
            >, shell redirects, <code
              class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
              >tee</code
            >. The Bash bypass is a filed issue (<code
              class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
              >claude-code#29709</code
            >) — matching Edit/Write only would be trivially defeated.
          </p>
          <p class="font-heading text-[11px] tracking-tight text-foreground">
            zero tokens · non-bypassable · can't degrade
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="grid gap-4 py-7 sm:grid-cols-[9rem_1fr] sm:gap-10">
        <div>
          <div
            class="font-heading text-[10px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-[color:var(--accent-amber)]"
          >
            layer 02
          </div>
          <div
            class="mt-1 font-heading text-base font-semibold text-foreground"
          >
            the primitive
          </div>
        </div>
        <div
          class="space-y-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground"
        >
          <p>
            Each mode's behavioral contract is split into a small core
            (roughly 800–2,000 tokens — Anthropic's persistence sweet spot)
            and a set of reference files loaded on demand via tool calls. The
            core lives in the highest-attention zone at the start of context.
            References arrive fresh at the end, where attention is strongest.
            The middle — where context rot bites — holds accumulated tool
            results and resolved conversation, where decay is correct.
          </p>
          <p class="font-heading text-[11px] tracking-tight text-foreground">
            in-context · degrades with length · catches what the hook can't
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="grid gap-4 py-7 sm:grid-cols-[9rem_1fr] sm:gap-10">
        <div>
          <div
            class="font-heading text-[10px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-[color:var(--accent-amber)]"
          >
            layer 03
          </div>
          <div
            class="mt-1 font-heading text-base font-semibold text-foreground"
          >
            session restart
          </div>
        </div>
        <div
          class="space-y-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground"
        >
          <p>
            When the session has drifted far enough that you notice, you
            restart. A fresh Claude Code window reads <code
              class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
              >.bocek/state.md</code
            > and the compiled vault and picks up at the last resolved
            decision. Not a blank slate — a continuation. Sessions are
            disposable, knowledge is permanent.
          </p>
          <p class="font-heading text-[11px] tracking-tight text-foreground">
            manual · full recovery · the vault is the memory
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p
      class="mt-10 max-w-2xl text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground"
    >
      Nothing registers until <code
        class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
        >bocek on</code
      >. No persona loaded, no skills attached, no always-on system prompt.
      Every token in context is a token you chose to load.
    </p>
  </ChapterHeading>

  <!-- 06 — the vault -->
  <ChapterHeading
    id="vault"
    number="06"
    title="The code is downstream. The vault is the product."
    kicker="the vault"
    variant="alt"
  >
    <p
      class="mb-10 max-w-2xl text-base leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground"
    >
      The vault is two representations of the same knowledge. The source of
      truth is Obsidian-style markdown — YAML frontmatter, wikilinks, optional
      feature folders — so humans can read and cross-reference it. A compiled
      per-feature layer is generated on demand by implementation mode when
      source files change. You never hand-edit the compiled layer. You commit
      the source.
    </p>

    <VaultCompare />

    <p
      class="mt-10 max-w-2xl text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground"
    >
      Two formats, one direction. Compilation is lazy — only when
      implementation mode needs the feature's compiled file, only if the
      source has changed. No sync step. No stale artifacts. The vault travels
      with the code; the compiled layer is gitignored because it's a build
      artifact, regenerable from the source.
    </p>
  </ChapterHeading>

  <!-- Getting started -->
  <section class="relative">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-6 py-20">
      <div class="mb-10 flex items-baseline gap-5">
        <span
          aria-hidden="true"
          class="font-heading text-sm font-semibold tracking-[0.2em] text-[color:var(--accent-amber)]"
          >07</span
        >
        <span class="h-px flex-1 bg-border/60"></span>
        <span
          class="font-heading text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.25em] text-muted-foreground"
          >getting started</span
        >
      </div>
      <h2
        class="mb-8 font-heading text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-foreground sm:text-4xl"
      >
        Install. Activate. Design something you can defend.
      </h2>
      <div class="space-y-4">
        <TerminalBlock command={installCmd} title="~ — install bocek" />
        <TerminalBlock
          command="cd your-project && bocek on"
          title="~/your-project"
        />
      </div>
      <p
        class="mt-6 max-w-2xl text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground"
      >
        Open Claude Code in the same directory. Run <code
          class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
          >/design</code
        > and start with a real decision — the one you've been avoiding.
        Requires git, curl, and jq. Nothing else gets touched until you
        activate a project.
      </p>
      <p
        class="mt-6 text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground"
      >
        The <a
          href="/guide"
          class="text-foreground underline decoration-border/60 underline-offset-4 transition-colors hover:decoration-[color:var(--accent-amber)]"
          >guide</a
        > walks a full checkout session end-to-end: design → research →
        implementation → review, with the vault files each mode produces.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
